---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import HeroSection from '../components/HeroSection.astro';
import CTAButton from '../components/CTAButton.astro';
import BookingButton from '../components/BookingButton.astro';
import BenefitCard from '../components/BenefitCard.astro';
import { Zap, Lightbulb, Heart, Check, FlaskConical } from '@lucide/astro';
import FAQSection from '../components/FAQSection.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="NAD+ IV Therapy"
  description="NAD+ is a coenzyme involved in cellular energy metabolism. Learn how monitored NAD+ IV therapy is used for selected patients in Halifax."
  focusKeyword="NAD therapy Halifax"
>
  <HeroSection
    title="NAD+ IV Therapy"
    compact
    image={{ src: "/images/treatments/nad-iv-therapy-session.webp", alt: "Patient receiving NAD+ IV therapy in Halifax", aspect: "video" }}
  >
    <p>NAD+ (nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide) is a coenzyme involved in energy metabolism and cellular signaling. NAD+ IV therapy is available in the practice for selected patients interested in a monitored infusion while the clinical research continues to develop.</p>
  </HeroSection>

  <!-- Three Benefits Section -->
  <section class="py-16 lg:py-24 bg-[#f7f7f5]">
    <div class="section-shell">
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6 lg:gap-8">
        <BenefitCard title="Established Biology">
          <Zap slot="icon" class="h-6 w-6" stroke-width={1.75} aria-hidden="true" />
          <p>NAD+ participates in the reactions cells use to transfer energy from nutrients. It is also a substrate for enzymes involved in cellular signaling and DNA repair.<sup>1-3</sup></p>
        </BenefitCard>

        <BenefitCard title="A Focused Infusion">
          <Lightbulb slot="icon" class="h-6 w-6" stroke-width={1.75} aria-hidden="true" />
          <p>NAD+ is infused gradually under clinical supervision. The rate can be adjusted throughout the appointment in response to comfort and tolerability.</p>
        </BenefitCard>

        <BenefitCard title="Individual Assessment">
          <Heart slot="icon" class="h-6 w-6" stroke-width={1.75} aria-hidden="true" />
          <p>The service is used for selected patients after reviewing health history, medications, goals and the important limits of current human evidence.</p>
        </BenefitCard>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What is NAD+ Section -->
  <section class="py-16 lg:py-24 bg-emerald-50">
    <div class="section-shell">
      <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-center">
        <div>
          <h2 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-serif font-medium text-emerald-950 mb-6">What is NAD+?</h2>
          <div class="prose prose-lg text-slate-600">
            <p>
              NAD+ (nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide) is a coenzyme present throughout the body. It helps transfer electrons during energy metabolism and is used by enzymes involved in cellular signaling and DNA repair.
            </p>
            <p>
              NAD+ metabolism changes with age and with a number of health conditions, although levels differ between tissues and cannot be inferred from symptoms alone.<sup>1-4</sup> Much of the enthusiasm around NAD+ comes from laboratory and animal research. Human trials have focused mainly on oral precursors such as nicotinamide riboside and nicotinamide mononucleotide rather than IV NAD+ itself.<sup>4,5</sup>
            </p>
            <p>
              IV administration places NAD+ directly into the bloodstream and avoids intestinal absorption. It does not yet follow that more NAD+ reaches every target tissue or that the infusion produces a particular clinical outcome; those questions require better human studies.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl overflow-hidden shadow-xl">
          <img
            src="/images/treatments/nad-cellular-energy.webp"
            width="1200"
            height="654"
            loading="lazy"
            decoding="async"
            alt="Active woman enjoying outdoor activities with renewed energy from NAD+ therapy"
            class="w-full h-full object-cover"
          />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Reasons patients ask section -->
  <section id="conditions-treated" class="py-16 lg:py-24 bg-white">
    <div class="section-shell">
      <div class="text-center mb-12">
        <h2 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-serif font-medium text-emerald-950 mb-4">Why Patients Ask About NAD+ Therapy</h2>
        <p class="text-lg text-slate-600 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
          Interest is often connected to energy, cognition, recovery or healthy aging. These goals are reviewed without assuming that one infusion can explain or resolve the underlying concern.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-start">
        <div class="bg-emerald-50 rounded-2xl p-8 card-hover">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-serif font-medium text-emerald-950 mb-4">Energy and Recovery</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Some patients are curious about NAD+ during periods of persistent fatigue, demanding schedules or recovery. Fatigue has many possible causes, so appropriate investigation and established treatment remain important.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-emerald-50 rounded-2xl p-8 card-hover">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-serif font-medium text-emerald-950 mb-4">Mental Clarity</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">Brain fog and reduced concentration are common reasons for interest. Clinical trials have not established IV NAD+ as a treatment for cognitive impairment, and new or progressive neurological symptoms require medical assessment.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-emerald-50 rounded-2xl p-8 card-hover">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-serif font-medium text-emerald-950 mb-4">Healthy-Aging Interest</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">NAD+ biology is closely studied in aging research. Most outcome data are preclinical or involve oral precursors, so IV NAD+ should not be described as reversing aging or preventing age-related disease.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-emerald-50 rounded-2xl p-8 card-hover">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-serif font-medium text-emerald-950 mb-4">A Supervised Trial</h3>
          <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">For a suitable patient who understands the uncertainty, a monitored and time-limited trial can provide a practical way to assess personal tolerability and response without committing to a predetermined series.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How NAD+ Works Section -->
  <section id="how-nad-works" class="py-16 lg:py-24 bg-emerald-950">
    <div class="section-shell">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-serif font-medium text-white mb-6">How Does NAD+ Work?</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-lg prose-invert">
          <p class="text-white/90">
            NAD+ functions as a critical coenzyme in cellular metabolism, shuttling electrons between molecules during energy production in the mitochondria. Without adequate NAD+, your cells cannot efficiently convert nutrients into usable energy (ATP).<sup>17-19</sup>
          </p>
          <p class="text-white/90">
            NAD+ is also consumed by sirtuins and PARP enzymes involved in cellular signaling and DNA repair. These mechanisms are scientifically important, but demonstrating a pathway is different from demonstrating that an IV infusion improves a symptom or health outcome.<sup>1-3</sup>
          </p>
          <p class="text-white/90">
            The central question for patients is not whether NAD+ matters—it does—but whether administering additional NAD+ intravenously provides a useful clinical benefit. Human evidence for IV NAD+ is still limited, so the service is offered with measured expectations and professional monitoring.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Why IV Administration Section -->
  <section class="py-16 lg:py-24 bg-white">
    <div class="section-shell">
      <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-center">
        <div class="rounded-2xl overflow-hidden shadow-xl order-2 lg:order-1">
          <img
            src="/images/treatments/nad-brain-clarity.webp"
            width="1200"
            height="821"
            loading="lazy"
            decoding="async"
            alt="Brain fog to mental clarity transformation with NAD+ therapy"
            class="w-full h-full object-cover"
          />
        </div>
        <div class="order-1 lg:order-2">
          <h2 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-serif font-medium text-emerald-950 mb-6">Why IV Administration?</h2>
          <div class="prose prose-lg text-slate-600">
            <p>
              Oral NAD+ precursors such as NMN and NR and intravenous NAD+ are different interventions. IV administration avoids intestinal absorption and creates immediate systemic exposure, while oral precursors rely on absorption and metabolism.
            </p>
            <p>
              It is not yet clear which route is best for a given goal or how much intact IV NAD+ reaches specific tissues. Studies of oral precursors should not be used as proof of IV NAD+ effectiveness, and higher blood exposure should not be equated automatically with a better outcome.
            </p>
            <p>
              A practical advantage of the IV route is that treatment takes place in a supervised setting and the rate can be adjusted. NAD+ is infused gradually because faster rates can cause nausea, abdominal cramping, warmth, increased heart rate or chest pressure in some people.<sup>6</sup>
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Pricing Section -->
  <section class="py-16 lg:py-24 bg-emerald-50">
    <div class="section-shell">
      <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-2 gap-12">
        <!-- NAD+ Therapy Card -->
        <div class="bg-white rounded-3xl shadow-xl p-8 lg:p-10 card-hover">
          <div class="text-center mb-6">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif font-medium text-emerald-950 mb-4">NAD+ IV Therapy</h2>
            <div class="flex justify-center mb-4">
              <FlaskConical class="w-20 h-20 text-emerald-950" stroke-width={1.5} aria-hidden="true" />
            </div>
            <p class="text-slate-600">A gradual, professionally monitored infusion</p>
          </div>

          <ul class="space-y-3 mb-8">
            <li class="flex items-center">
              <Check class="w-5 h-5 text-emerald-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true" />
              <span>Pure NAD+ coenzyme</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-center">
              <Check class="w-5 h-5 text-emerald-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true" />
              <span>Direct bloodstream administration</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-center">
              <Check class="w-5 h-5 text-emerald-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true" />
              <span>Rate adjusted for tolerability</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-center">
              <Check class="w-5 h-5 text-emerald-600 mr-3 flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true" />
              <span>Professional monitoring</span>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Getting Started Card -->
        <div class="bg-white rounded-3xl shadow-xl p-8 lg:p-10 card-hover">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif font-medium text-emerald-950 mb-6">Getting Started with NAD+ Therapy</h2>

          <p class="text-slate-600 mb-8">
            To ensure that NAD+ therapy is appropriate for you, an initial naturopathic consultation is required. This allows us to review your health history, discuss your goals and create a personalized treatment plan.
          </p>

          <BookingButton variant="secondary" size="lg" fullWidth source="nad-therapy-pricing" />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Research Evidence Section -->
  <section class="py-16 lg:py-24 bg-white">
    <div class="section-shell">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-serif font-medium text-emerald-950 mb-6">The Science Behind NAD+</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-lg text-slate-600">
          <p>
            Research has established the importance of NAD+ metabolism and has generated considerable interest in ways to influence it. The strength of evidence depends on what is being studied:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Cell biology:</strong> NAD+ has well-established roles in energy metabolism, sirtuin activity and PARP-dependent processes.<sup>1-3</sup></li>
            <li><strong>Animal research:</strong> Raising NAD+ or providing precursors has produced interesting metabolic and aging-related findings in several models, but animal results do not establish human treatment effects.<sup>2,3</sup></li>
            <li><strong>Human precursor trials:</strong> Oral NR and NMN can alter NAD-related biomarkers and have generally been tolerated in short trials. Clinical benefits have been variable and are not evidence for IV NAD+ itself.<sup>4,5</sup></li>
            <li><strong>IV NAD+:</strong> Direct human research remains sparse. A small 2026 retrospective commercial-clinic study focused mainly on tolerability and short-term laboratory markers; it was not designed to establish symptom improvement or long-term effectiveness.<sup>6</sup></li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            This is a promising research area, but the evidence does not yet support claims that IV NAD+ reliably improves energy, cognition, addiction outcomes or longevity. In the practice, it is used for selected patients who remain interested after those limitations are discussed.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What to Expect Section -->
  <section class="py-16 lg:py-24 bg-emerald-50">
    <div class="section-shell">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-serif font-medium text-emerald-950 mb-8 text-center">What to Expect</h2>

        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6 lg:gap-8">
          <div class="text-center">
            <div class="w-16 h-16 bg-emerald-700 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-4">
              <span class="text-2xl font-bold text-white">1</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-emerald-950 mb-2">Before Your Infusion</h3>
            <p class="text-slate-600">Eat a light meal, stay hydrated and follow the instructions provided for your formula. Wear comfortable clothing with easy arm access.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="text-center">
            <div class="w-16 h-16 bg-emerald-700 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-4">
              <span class="text-2xl font-bold text-white">2</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-emerald-950 mb-2">During Your Infusion</h3>
            <p class="text-slate-600">The infusion is given gradually. Tell the clinician immediately about nausea, cramping, warmth, a racing heart, chest pressure or any other discomfort so the infusion can be paused or adjusted.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="text-center">
            <div class="w-16 h-16 bg-emerald-700 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mx-auto mb-4">
              <span class="text-2xl font-bold text-white">3</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-emerald-950 mb-2">After Your Infusion</h3>
            <p class="text-slate-600">Most people resume their usual activities if they feel well. Note any changes in symptoms or function afterward; benefit is not assumed and a predetermined series is not required.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Safety Section -->
  <section class="py-16 lg:py-24 bg-emerald-950">
    <div class="section-shell">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-serif font-medium text-white mb-6">Safety of NAD+ Therapy</h2>
        <div class="prose prose-lg prose-invert">
          <p class="text-white/90">
            Published safety information for commercial IV NAD+ remains limited. Being naturally present in the body does not make an intravenous dose automatically risk-free, which is why screening, gradual administration and monitoring matter.
          </p>
          <p class="text-white/90">
            Reported infusion effects include nausea, abdominal cramping, diarrhea, warmth, increased heart rate and chest or throat pressure. In a small retrospective study these symptoms resolved when infusions ended, but the study was too small to define uncommon or long-term risks.<sup>6</sup>
          </p>
          <p class="text-white/90">
            Treatment may not be appropriate during pregnancy or breastfeeding or with certain cardiac, kidney, cancer-related or other significant medical considerations. A health assessment and medication review are completed before treatment. New or concerning symptoms should be medically evaluated rather than attributed to low NAD+.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FAQSection bg="white" items={[
          { question: "How long does an NAD+ infusion take?", answer: "<p>NAD+ infusions are administered gradually and may take approximately 1–4 hours depending on the dose and individual tolerability. The rate is adjusted throughout the appointment.</p>" },
          { question: "How many treatments will I need?", answer: "<p>There is no evidence-based universal series. If you are a suitable candidate, the initial plan can be kept limited and reassessed according to tolerability, cost and whether you notice a meaningful change.</p>" },
          { question: "What does NAD+ therapy feel like?", answer: "<p>Some people tolerate the infusion comfortably, while others experience nausea, cramping, warmth, increased heart rate or chest pressure. These symptoms must be reported promptly and often improve when the infusion is slowed or stopped. Experiences after treatment vary.</p>" },
          { question: "Is NAD+ therapy different from taking NAD+ supplements?", answer: "<p>Yes. IV NAD+, oral NAD+ and precursors such as NMN or NR use different routes and are metabolized differently. Direct bloodstream administration does not by itself prove better cellular uptake or better clinical results.</p>" },
          { question: "Who should not receive NAD+ therapy?", answer: "<p>It may not be appropriate during pregnancy or breastfeeding or for people with certain cardiac, kidney, cancer-related or other significant medical conditions. Suitability is determined only after an individual assessment.</p>" },
        ]} />

  <!-- References Section -->
  <section class="py-12 lg:py-16 bg-white">
    <div class="section-shell">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-serif font-medium text-emerald-950 mb-6">References</h2>
        <div class="text-slate-600 text-sm space-y-2">
          <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 space-y-1">
            <li>Yoshino J, Baur JA, Imai SI. NAD+ Intermediates: The Biology and Therapeutic Potential of NMN and NR. Cell Metab. 2018;27(3):513-528.</li>
            <li>Cantó C, Menzies KJ, Auwerx J. NAD(+) Metabolism and the Control of Energy Homeostasis: A Balancing Act between Mitochondria and the Nucleus. Cell Metab. 2015;22(1):31-53.</li>
            <li>Verdin E. NAD+ in aging, metabolism and neurodegeneration. Science. 2015;350(6265):1208-1213.</li>
            <li>Gindri IM, Ferrari G, Pinto LPS, et al. Evaluation of safety and effectiveness of NAD in different clinical conditions: a systematic review. Am J Physiol Endocrinol Metab. 2024;326(4):E417-E427.</li>
            <li>Li Y, et al. The therapeutic perspective of NAD+ precursors in age-related diseases. Cell Commun Signal. 2024;22:70.</li>
            <li>Reyna K, Heinzen G, Patel N, et al. Intravenous infusion of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+) versus nicotinamide riboside (NR): a retrospective tolerability pilot study in a real-world setting. Front Aging. 2026;7:1652582.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA Section -->
  <section class="py-16 lg:py-24 bg-emerald-950">
    <div class="section-shell text-center">
      <h2 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-serif font-medium text-white mb-6">Interested in NAD+ Therapy?</h2>
      <p class="text-lg text-emerald-200 max-w-2xl mx-auto mb-8">
        Book a consultation to review your goals, the current evidence and whether a monitored NAD+ infusion is a reasonable option for you.
      </p>
      <CTAButton source="nad-therapy-cta" />
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
